{
  "query": "In what ways do the reported outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography on artificial structures differ between intertidal studies in the UK and subtidal studies in Italy?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, there are several key differences between the reported outcomes of creating natural rocky reef topography on artificial structures in UK intertidal studies versus Italian subtidal studies:\n\nUK intertidal studies (Action ID 3435) found mixed results across multiple biodiversity measures. These studies found that creating natural rocky reef topography on intertidal artificial structures did not increase the combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness on structure surfaces. However, the intervention had mixed effects on barnacle and mobile invertebrate abundances on structure surfaces, depending on the site. Additionally, UK studies reported that natural topography created on intertidal artificial structures was colonized by macroalgae and limpets, and that limpets used shaded grooves and water-retaining depressions created by the topography.\n\nIn contrast, the Italian subtidal study (Action ID 3446) focused specifically on algal response and found that creating natural rocky reef topography on subtidal artificial structures did not increase the abundance of juvenile canopy macroalgae that settled onto structure surfaces, regardless of the topography depth.\n\nThe key differences are: (1) UK intertidal studies examined broader community responses including both macroalgae and invertebrates, while the Italian subtidal study focused only on algal abundance; (2) UK studies found evidence of functional habitat use by limpets utilizing the created topographical features, while the Italian study did not report behavioral or habitat use outcomes; (3) UK studies showed site-dependent effects on invertebrate abundance, suggesting variability in effectiveness, while the Italian study showed consistently no effect on algal settlement regardless of topography depth.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3435",
    "3446"
  ]
}

