{
  "query": "What are the observed effects on invertebrate abundance when using environmentally-sensitive materials on artificial marine structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "Studies examining environmentally-sensitive materials on artificial marine structures show mixed effects on invertebrate abundance. For intertidal structures, action 3469 found that using hemp-concrete or shell-concrete in place of standard-concrete increased the combined macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate abundance on structure surfaces. The same action found that using limestone-cement, along with creating pits, grooves, small ridges and texture, or altering the composition of concrete had mixed effects on mobile invertebrate and/or barnacle abundance, depending on the site, wave-exposure and/or the type of material tested. For subtidal structures, action 3470 reported that using quarried rock or shell-concrete in place of standard-concrete did not increase the combined macroalgae and invertebrate abundance on structure surfaces in three of seven studies. However, two studies found mixed effects, depending on the type of quarried rock or concrete tested and/or the location. One study found that using ECOncrete in place of fibreglass, along with creating textured surfaces, increased the live cover and biomass. Specifically for invertebrate abundance, action 3470 found that using quarried rock in place of concrete on subtidal artificial structures, or using ECOncrete, along with creating grooves, holes and pits, had mixed effects on the abundance of non-mobile invertebrates, mobile invertebrates or coral recruits on structure surfaces, depending on the type of rock tested, the species group and/or the site. Action 2259 found that artificial reefs made of different materials showed no differences in overall invertebrate abundances between reef structure and/or material in four controlled studies, though one study found that \"sea-friendly\" concrete pyramids had lower abundance compared to plinth-pole structures after two years, but higher after three.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3469",
    "3470",
    "2259"
  ]
}

