{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effects of ceasing or altering maintenance activities on artificial marine structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence for the effects of ceasing or altering maintenance activities on artificial marine structures is limited and varies by habitat type. For intertidal artificial structures, no studies were found that evaluated the effects of ceasing or altering maintenance activities on biodiversity (Action 3440). For subtidal artificial structures, two studies examined these effects - one in an estuary in southeast Australia and one in an inland bay in eastern USA (Action 3447). In subtidal environments, reducing the frequency of cleaning on artificial structures did not alter overall invertebrate and fish community composition, species richness, diversity, or abundance on and around structure surfaces (Action 3447). However, reducing cleaning frequency increased macroalgal abundance on structure surfaces (Action 3447). When the area cleaned on subtidal artificial structures was reduced, seahorse abundance on structure surfaces increased (Action 3447). Reduced cleaning frequency did not increase survival or growth of transplanted oysters (Action 3447).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3440",
    "3447"
  ]
}

