{
  "query": "When creating flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures, what are the comparative effects of using short versus long materials?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on studies examining flexible habitats on subtidal artificial structures, there are notable differences between short (1-50 mm) and long (>50 mm) materials. Short flexible habitats had mixed effects on mobile and non-mobile invertebrate community composition and abundance, with effects varying depending on density, length, site, and survey timing (Action 3450). Long flexible habitats supported macroalgae and non-mobile invertebrate or fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without flexible habitats (Action 3451). Long flexible habitats supported higher combined macroalgae and invertebrate biomass than structure surfaces without flexible habitats, with deeper flexible habitats supporting higher biomass than shallower ones (Action 3451). While both short and long flexible habitats had mixed effects on invertebrate abundance, long flexible habitats specifically decreased mussel abundance on structure surfaces but the flexible habitats themselves supported higher biomass, mostly mussels, than the structure surfaces (Action 3451). Long flexible habitats were also documented as being used by seahorses (Action 3451), whereas short flexible habitats showed mixed effects on seahorse abundance depending on survey week (Action 3450). Fish species richness showed mixed effects with long flexible habitats depending on fish presence when habitats were created, while short flexible habitats did not increase mobile or non-mobile invertebrate species richness (Action 3450).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3450",
    "3451"
  ]
}

