{
  "query": "In northern Israel, how do the effects of creating pit habitats (1-50 mm) compare with creating hole habitats (>50 mm) on subtidal artificial structures?",
  "relevant_summary": "In northern Israel, both pit habitats (1-50 mm) and hole habitats (>50 mm) on subtidal artificial structures showed similar positive effects on community composition and species diversity. Action 3455 reports that pit habitats, when created along with holes, grooves and environmentally-sensitive material, altered the combined macroalgae and invertebrate community composition on structure surfaces and supported mobile and non-mobile invertebrate and fish species that were absent from structures without added habitat features. Similarly, Action 3434 reports that hole habitats, along with grooves, environmentally-sensitive material and pits, altered the combined macroalgae and invertebrate community composition on and around structures and supported mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate and/or fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without added habitat features. Both habitat types increased species diversity, with Action 3455 showing that pit habitats increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species diversity on structure surfaces, while Action 3434 found that hole habitats increased combined macroalgae and invertebrate species richness and/or diversity on and around structures. Regarding population responses, both habitat types had mixed effects on species abundances. Action 3455 reports that pit habitats had mixed effects on macroalgal, invertebrate, and fish abundances depending on the species group. Action 3434 similarly reports that hole habitats had mixed effects on macroalgal abundances, invertebrate abundances, and fish abundances, depending on the species group. However, Action 3434 specifically found that hole habitats increased the abundance of brown crabs on and around structures, but not other mobile invertebrates.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3434",
    "3455"
  ]
}

