{
  "query": "How do the biodiversity outcomes of creating 'rock pools' on intertidal artificial structures vary by location?",
  "relevant_summary": "Creating rock pools on intertidal artificial structures shows variable biodiversity outcomes across different geographical locations. Studies were conducted across multiple regions: ten studies in estuaries in Australia, the UK and eastern USA; five on open coastlines in the UK, Ireland and southeast Spain; two in straits in the UK and Malaysia; and one in a marina in Australia (Action 3476).\n\nLocation-specific outcomes include: In Ireland, shore level and wave-exposure affected community composition, with wave-sheltered pools filling with sediment within two years (Action 3476). In Australia, the effectiveness varied by pool depth, shore level and site, with mixed effects on community composition depending on these factors (Action 3476). Studies in Australia, the UK, Spain and Malaysia found that rock pools generally supported macroalgae, mobile invertebrate, non-mobile invertebrate and/or fish species that were absent from structure surfaces without pools (Action 3476).\n\nThe studies showed that nine of 12 replicated, controlled studies in Australia, the UK, Spain and Malaysia found rock pools supported higher combined macroalgae, invertebrate and/or fish species diversity and/or richness than structure surfaces without pools, though three studies reported similar species richness between pools and structure surfaces (Action 3476). Location also influenced functional outcomes, with one study finding that functional richness was lower in high-shore pools than mid-shore pools (Action 3476).\n\nPool characteristics interacted differently with environmental conditions across locations - two studies found pool depth did not affect community composition, while wave exposure and shore level had varying effects depending on the specific site location (Action 3476). The effectiveness of rock pools in supporting biodiversity appears to be influenced by local environmental conditions including wave exposure, shore level, and site-specific factors that vary by geographical region.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3476"
  ]
}

